Edit /etc/rsyslog.d/umrs.conf


------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Load the mmjsonparse module if not already loaded
module(load="mmjsonparse")

# Define a template that exports the entire journal entry as JSON
template(name="json-template" type="list") {
    property(name="$!all-json")
    constant(value="\n")
}

# Filter for your specific tag and write to the file
if $programname == 'umrs' then {
    action(type="omfile" file="/var/log/umrs.log" template="json-template")
    stop # Optional: prevents these logs from also going to /var/log/messages
}

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Create the file and give rsyslog ownership
sudo touch /var/log/umrs.log
sudo chown root:adm /var/log/umrs.log
sudo chmod 640 /var/log/umrs.log
sudo restorecon -v /var/log/umrs.log

# Restart rsyslog
sudo systemctl restart rsyslog


Use rsyslogd -N1 to check for errors.



In the world of syslog and systemd, the "importance" of a log message is defined by two specific integer fields: Priority and Facility.
1. The Definitions
Priority (PRIORITY): Defines the severity (how bad is it?).
Facility (SYSLOG_FACILITY): Defines the source (who sent it?).
Combined, these are often referred to as the Priority Value (PRIVAL).
2. Priority (Severity) Levels
These are the standard levels used by both the Rust log crate and journalctl.
Value	String (Enum)	Description
0	emerg / emergency	System is unusable.
1	alert	Action must be taken immediately.
2	crit / critical	Critical conditions (hardware/software).
3	err / error	Error conditions.
4	warning	Warning conditions.
5	notice	Normal but significant condition.
6	info	Informational messages.
7	debug	Debug-level messages.
3. Facility (Source) Levels
Since your program is a user-space application, it almost certainly defaults to user (1).
Value	String (Enum)	Typical Source
0	kern	Kernel messages.
1	user	Generic user-level messages (Your App).
2	mail	Mail system.
3	daemon	System daemons.
4	auth	Security/authorization.
9	cron	Clock daemon.
16-23	local0-local7	Reserved for local use/custom routing.


4. How to see these in your JSON
If you want to see the human-readable strings (like "info") instead of just the number "6" in your /var/log/umrs.log, you can modify your rsyslog template to use specific property names:
%syslogpriority-text%: Exports "info", "error", etc.
%syslogfacility-text%: Exports "user", "daemon", etc.
5. In your Rust Code
When you use log::info!(), the systemd-journal-logger automatically:
Maps the Rust Level::Info to Priority 6.
Usually defaults the Facility to 1 (user).


Log Level to Priority Mapping 
While many systems use a 1:1 mapping, this crate shifts the values to align with systemd's specific expectations for internal journal metadata. 
