Rust log::Level 	Syslog Priority (Value)	Syslog Name
Level::Error	3	err
Level::Warn	4	warning
Level::Info	5	notice
Level::Debug	6	info
Level::Trace	7	debug
Key Fields & Defaults
When your message reaches the journal (and subsequently your /var/log/umrs.log), the following mappings are applied by the crate: 
www.loggly.com
www.loggly.com
 +1
SYSLOG_FACILITY: Defaults to 1 (user). This is the standard facility for user-space applications.
SYSLOG_IDENTIFIER: By default, this is your binary name (e.g., mcs-translator). You have already overridden this to umrs-mcs using .with_syslog_identifier().
SYSLOG_PID: Automatically captured as your current process ID.
MESSAGE: The formatted string you passed to the log! macro. 
www.loggly.com
www.loggly.com
 +3
Mapping Note
Notice that Level::Info maps to notice (5), not info (6). If you find your rsyslog filters are slightly "off," it is likely because of this one-step shift in priority values. If you want to see standard "info" level messages in the journal, you actually need to use log::debug!() in your Rust code. 
